<br>
That said, I will elaborate. The Pledge issue was the most recent debate I saw... this is a hard one because although I agree that those who don't believe in God shouldn't have to say &quot;under God&quot;, I don't think that those who do believe in God shouldn't be permitted to. <br>
<br>
It gets so sketchy because if you have religious types in a public meeting who want to pray, those who oppose prayer in public meetings are mad. Yet, should those who want to pray not be allowed to because it makes someone else uncomfortable or feel excluded? I think you have to be careful that in ensuring one side isn't excluded that you take away the right to religion for the other side. <br>
<br>
Also, most people can't separate their religion from the rest of themselves. As a believer in God, I can't walk into a public meeting, government building, or school and leave my religion at the door. It affects the choices I make, it affects what I believe to be best, and it affects my attitudes. Although I think the separation is a good thing, I think it is difficult to do without stripping one side or the other of their rights. <br>
<br>
Personally, I would have no problem with a teacher who is athiest telling my child that they don't believe in God, a Jewish teacher telling my child that they don't believe in Christ, or even a homosexual teacher telling my child that they have a partner of the same gender. I don't understant why those who don't believe in God don't want their child told that the teacher does believe in God. We, as parents, are responsible for teaching our children and I personally have confidence in what I teach my child. I don't think that a teacher telling my child that he/she doesn't believe in God would change her belief system. I don't think, however, that any religion should run things in government or that a school should teach that the doctrines of one religion, etc are truth. Giving information about other belief systems only makes us wiser, more well-rounded and better off, imo.<br>
<br>
Sorry that this is extremely choppy and rambled. Just typing off the top of my head and for some reason, I have trouble articulating my thoughts on this subject.<br>
