I totally agree and maybe didn't articulate that very well... I would actually like my children to be taught about other belief systems. I don't subscribe to the &quot;ignorance is bliss&quot; theory. I would way rather my child receive information about other religions. I never said that they should be teaching whether or not it was true or given any opinions on the matter. But I think that any information that is subjective should not be presented with a teachers pov as the reference. I had a psychology teacher in college who gave her opinion on every single theory. For instance, Freud. She thought he was a quack. Anyone in that introductory class left it believing that Freud was just that. I happen to think that Freud had some very valid theories but that people take them out of the context he presented them. Facts are one thing, trying to sway opinions is a totally different story. I never said that I supported teaching religion in school, only teaching about different belief systems.<br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;That the exact reason why I support SOCAS. Because then who gets to decide what religion is best? I don't want decisions about country made because how someone feels about god or because the bible says its so. &lt;&lt; <br>
<br>
The only way to avoid that happening is to elect officials who feel the way you do or to petition the elected officials and hope they listen. Unfortunately, if you have officials in government who believe that abortion is wrong because of the bible or otherwise, they will fight for that stance. How can you separate church and state when the officials belief systems are going to dictate how the stand on key issues? <br>
<br>
I feel exactly the same about legislation. In the last presidential election, I did not vote for Bush. I agree with him on many of the *moral* issues but agreed with Gore on more of the social/financial issues. I happen to believe that you cannot legislate morality. You can make things illegal but that won't stop people from doing them. Abortion is one of those issues. Although I oppose it, I don't see how making it illegal will stop people from doing it. They will just do it illegally. People have to make their own choices on moral issues. But on the same note, I think we would be hard pressed to find a politician or political leader who would take what his constituents say and vote based on that if it stood in the face of his religious beliefs. So although SOCAS would work in a perfect world, it has shortfalls when trying to institute it in the world we live in. Just as other laws are only as good as people observances of such laws, SOCAS is one that unless people grab hold of and believe strongly in (as I know Emmy does <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) they just aren't as effective as they should be. <br>
<br>
