Does that mean that the teacher or principal is then not allowed to say the words? If she/he does, would it be considered leading the children? Where is the line drawn? <br>
<br>
&gt;&gt;Teaching about a belief system is one thing, teaching a belief system as fact or truth is an entirely different matter, and too fine of a line for many teachers to be able to see clearly, IMO.&lt;&lt;<br>
<br>
And that was EXACTLY what I was trying to say in regards to teaching *about* belief systems. However, where do you draw the line on what can be taught and what can't? My World History Class taught a lot about the ancient Catholic Church. Here in Utah, the Utah History classes, if you take out the Mormons, there would be relatively no Utah History. You would have to take Darwin out of the Science books, and anything which could be debated out of any other class. The softer sciences of psychology, sociology, etc, could all be eliminated because they are prone to interpretation and the opinion of the person teaching them. I agree that there should not be teachers passing on their beliefs for or against any belief system or group of people. To do so, imo, is discriminatory. But where do you stop the slippery slope? I would really like to know. Because this is one of those instances where you look at it from one side and it looks totally different than it does from the other side. <br>
<br>
Although I agree that it is wrong for a teacher, leader, etc to lead prayers, discussions, pledges that might exclude someone, I also see that it limits the rights of those who are leading. Maybe I am off base here. Can a teacher in a classroom actually say &quot;under God&quot; during the pledge if she doesn't try to get the other kids to do so? Or is she to not say those words because it might be perceived as leading them? <br>
<br>
I can place myself on the other side of the coin and see how it would feel. There are many &quot;energetic&quot; religious types, especially some Christian groups, who won't leave others well enough alone and who are constantly pushing their views, trying to force others to conform to their way of thinking and that would get extremely old. Also, I can see where, for the most part, especially where I am from (UT) that there would not be very many voices which advocate a stance other than mainstream (although that is changing). However, on the flip side, can you see why Christians, who love their God, believe in Him and do worship Him would be frustrated at the least and somewhat passionate about what seems like an effort to remove Him? Although I understand why you say &quot;He&quot; should have never been part of it in the first place... I still find it hard to remove God from schools, courts, govt. buildings and meetings without removing those who believe in Him. <br>
<br>
Unfortunately, we don't live in a world where tolerance is what is popular. I personally don't understand that. I believe that every person should have a right to believe what they choose. I am happy to share my beliefs if someone wants to know about them. I welcome that opportunity but I do not see the point in pushing my beliefs on others. They have a right to believe whatever and however they want to. And I believe that is a God-given right, or one that should be inherent to all of us simply because no person or person's beliefs should be placed above another. <br>
<br>
Anyway, again, this is one subject I don't articulate very well on but I am trying. So bring on the rebuts!<br>
