&gt;&gt;school should be all about skepticism, inquiry and debate&lt;&lt;  <br>
<br>
yes, that is what it should be about but most elementary, secondary, and post secondary schools are more concerned with moving students through, teaching the basic curriculum of reading, writing, math, english, science, etc. They do not, at least in my experience, spend much time worrying about even teaching students how to debate. Skeptisism is punishable, and there is not time for real inquiry. So, while school should be about those things, it is not. And maybe it is because I am Christian that I don't remember being preached to, unless it was my Seminary class that was before school that I used as an excuse to go out to breakfast.<br>
<br>
The thing that bothers me most about the tone of your post is that you are grouping me in with other Christians like Mom Loves Um who spend their entire life &quot;witnessing&quot; to people who don't want to hear it. I have never been one to go with the flow. I have questioned and gone against everything I was taught as a child by my parents and eventually made the decision to come back. I angered my AP English teacher in high school because we had to read a book in which there were many Christian symbols which he wanted us to pick out. It was &quot;The Old Man in the Sea&quot;. I was angry because I saw things differently than he did but unless I saw them as he did (and he was a Mormon bishop), he said I was wrong. I confronted him in front of the entire class. I asked why he was the expert. Why he thought that his analysis of the book was better than mine. I asked why if we were going to study great authors, why didn't we study Dr. Seuss, who was less likely to disclude anyone. He swore at me and asked me to leave. It is the mentality of him and people like him who believe that they are right and to Hell with anyone else that gives all Christians a bad name. I do not feel that way. I do not advocate teaching or preaching religion.  But for some reason you seem to think that I have said that we should be leading children in prayer and preaching God to them and indoctrinating them in schools and public places when I have clearly said the opposite. <br>
<br>
All I was trying to say is that when you have people who believe in something, you can not have a society completely absent of that object of belief. Whether it be God, Buddah, Allah, The Great Ape, I don't care. I agree that no person of authority should be leading children to much of anything. They are to present facts. Plain and simple... no matter what the subject. That is the only way to allow students/children to be able to objectively make their own decisions about the material presented. <br>
<br>
Why can't you see that I am not saying what you are accusing me of? Is it so incomprehesible that a Christian (which to most Christians is not accepted as Christian) would not want Christianity or anything else preached in the classroom?<br>
